As for the lung cancer, I have NEVER, not once in all my research, heard marijuana blamed for lung cancer.  I'll check into it, and see what chemicals it is that actually causes lung cancer . . . there are a myriad of them in cigarrettes, you know.<br>
<br>
As for the addiction comment . . . you probably need to define the word &quot;addicting&quot; specifically.  If a &quot;people use/do it every day&quot; is the benchmark, then all sorts or ridiculous things are &quot;addictive&quot;:<br>
<br>
movies<br>
television<br>
driving a car<br>
riding in a plane<br>
riding in a boat<br>
sitting in a chair<br>
brushing your teeth<br>
EVERQUEST<br>
checking email<br>
chatting in AIM of ICQ<br>
cooking dinner<br>
eating in a restaurant<br>
etc <br>
<br>
The generally accepted definition for addictive chemicals is one that makes your body crave more of the chemical: nicotine, heroin, etc.  Marijuana has no such properties - it just gives people a feeling they like, which they want again - much like eating chocolate.<br>
<br>
